2016 IL Financial Contributions to Presidential Campaigns version 2

Sunny Jiang

November 10, 2017

Data sources

This report explores a dataset of 2016 Illinois Financial Contributions to Presidential Campaigns, which including 250K records. For details please refer to this website: http://classic.fec.gov/disclosurep/pnational.do

Data Explore and Analysis

Univariate

Heatmap and box plot for contribution amount to decipt outliers

To elimate the noise, we can plot only the ones within 1% to 99% percentile. We can see most contribution amounts are within $0 to $1000 range, after zoom in we can see most amount are actully less than $250.

From the the first boxplot we can see, this dataset has a few data points that incorrectly mapped to Illinois. And when plot the count by county for IL. Cook county contirbutes most of the contributions.

From two bar charts we can see most people only contributed less than 3 times. And only supported 1 candidate.

Bivariate

Take a closer look through the heatmap: 55% of people only contributed once to one candidate and covers 41% of total contribution amount in IL.

Contribution amount distribution for each candidate. Cruz has the highest contribution amount.

From these two bar charts, we can see Clinton, Sanders, Cruz and Trump are the top 4 condidates by both contribution count and amount

Contribution amount distribution for each county, this chart is too busy to see anything. So I tried treemap.

From these two treemap charts, we can see Cook County has the highest contribution amount. When I broke down to City and zipcode level for Cook County, Chicago is the top 1. Size corresponds to Amount and Color corresponds to Count.

Multivariate

For our top 4 candidates:

Bernie Sanders announced that he plan to seek the Democratic Partys nomination for President of the United States on May 26, 2015. On June 14, 2016, following the final primary election, Clinton became the presumptive Democratic nominee. As we can see from the time series chart, contribution made for Sanders were between May 2015 to July 2016, peaked on March 2016. Matches his campaign timeline.

Hillary Clinton announced her presidential campaign on April 12, 2015. Nominated as the presumptive nominee of the Demoratic Party on July 26, 2016. Conceded the election to Republican Donald Trump on November 9. The contribution amount to her was the highest all the time, expect for exceeded by Sanders on March and April 2016.

Ted Cruz announced his presidential campaign on March 23, 2015. And suspended his campaign late April 2016. The contribution amount to him were higher than to Trump until he suspended his campaign.

Donald Trump formally launched his campaign on June 16, 2015. On May 3, 2016 Trump became the presumptive nominee of the Republican Party, and elected as president on November 8, 2016. From the chart we can see, contribution to him was really low at the beginning and started to take off on May 2016 after he became the presumptive nominee of Republican Party.

Then study the distirbution for top 4 candidates with boxplot. Sanders has the lowest median contribution amount around $60. We can see some darker lines at $10, $30 and $100 which means a lot of contribution at those amounts. While Clinton has the hightest median contribution amount around $100, and have a lot of contributed at $50, $100, $500 and $2500. The highest contribution amount is $27000, and contributed to Cruz.

The first treemap shows that for Cook County, most of the contribtuion went to Clinton, then Sanders. From the second one, we can see Clinton had most of all the contribtutions. Trump and Sanders had similar amount.

I picked the top 10 counties with the highest contribution amount. And used boxplot and barchart to see the distiribtution for top 4 candidates. Contritubiton to Clinton from Cook county really dominated it. But in some counties like Peoria, the contirbution to Trump was higher.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

For 2016 Presidency Campaign, Sanders, Clinton, Cruz and Trump were the top 4 candidates by contribution amount and count. This shows the contirubtion amount for these 4 leading candidates overtime. Clint has the highest amount all the time except for exceeded by Sanders on March and April 2016. This might be able to indicate her winning of Illinois electoral votes.

Bernie Sanders announced that he plan to seek the Democratic Partys nomination for President of the United States on May 26, 2015. On June 14, 2016, following the final primary election, Clinton became the presumptive Democratic nominee. As we can see from the time series chart, contribution made for Sanders were between May 2015 to July 2016, peaked on March 2016. Matches his campaign timeline.

Hillary Clinton announced her presidential campaign on April 12, 2015. Nominated as the presumptive nominee of the Demoratic Party on July 26, 2016. Conceded the election to Republican Donald Trump on November 9. The contribution amount to her was the highest all the time, expect for exceeded by Sanders on March and April 2016.

Ted Cruz announced his presidential campaign on March 23, 2015. And suspended his campaign late April 2016. The contribution amount to him were higher than to Trump until he suspended his campaign.

Donald Trump formally launched his campaign on June 16, 2015. On May 3, 2016 Trump became the presumptive nominee of the Republican Party, and elected as president on November 8, 2016. From the chart we can see, contribution to him was really low at the beginning and started to take off on May 2016 after he became the presumptive nominee of Republican Party.

Plot Two

Then study the distirbution for top 4 candidates with boxplot. Sanders has the lowest median contribution amount around $60. We can see some darker lines at $10, $30 and $100 which means a lot of contribution at those amounts. While Clinton has the hightest median contribution amount around $100, and have a lot of contributed at $50, $100, $500 and $2500. The highest contribution amount is $27000, and contributed to Cruz.

Plot Three

55% of people only contributed once to one candidate and covers 41% of total contribution amount in IL. This tells us for most people making contirbution was a one time only thing through a campaign event. Less amount of people made contirbution repetitively or supported multiple candidates over time

Reflection

  • Since Im living in Peoira Illinois, I choosed Illinois data for this study.
  • I know Clint won the Illinois electoral votes, so I assumed she got most of the contribution. Which turns out true.
  • When I tried to map the location by zip code, I noticed that there are a few records that actually outside Illinois. For future exploration I should eliminate those records up front.
  • Another idea is group the zip code by county and compare with the final results. So we can see in detail whether the contribution amount affects the final results.
